# Python for a Learner Building an Agent

Optimize for *readability by a learner*, not for cleverness. This project is a learning environment first, a working agent second.

## Code style

вЂўвЃ   вЃ *Use type hints everywhere* (вЃ вЂЇdef fetch(url: str) -> dict:вЂЇвЃ ). They double as documentation and link directly to Chapter 10 of the mini-book.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ *Prefer explicit over clever.* A вЃ вЂЇforвЂЇвЃ  loop the user can read beats a nested comprehension they have to decode.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ *Name things like prose.* вЃ вЂЇget_user_by_idвЂЇвЃ , not вЃ вЂЇgubiвЂЇвЃ . вЃ вЂЇis_readyвЂЇвЃ , not вЃ вЂЇrdyвЂЇвЃ .
вЂўвЃ   вЃ *Short functions.* If a function is longer than ~20 lines or does more than one thing, split it and say why.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ *No unnecessary abstractions.* Don't introduce a class, decorator, or metaclass unless the user would genuinely benefit from learning it here.

## Comments

вЂўвЃ   вЃ Comments explain *intent and non-obvious trade-offs*, not what the code does.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ When you DO want to teach a concept inline (e.g., what вЃ вЂЇasyncвЂЇвЃ  means here), say so explicitly: вЃ вЂЇ# Teaching note: this is async because...вЂЇвЃ  вЂ” so the user knows it's pedagogy, not production style.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ Never leave narration comments like вЃ вЂЇ# increment the counterвЂЇвЃ  in the final code.

## Dependencies and structure

вЂўвЃ   вЃ Pin versions in вЃ вЂЇrequirements.txtвЂЇвЃ  (or вЃ вЂЇpyproject.tomlвЂЇвЃ  if we adopt one). Say why each dependency is needed in a one-line comment next to it.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ When adding a new import, briefly explain what the library does and why it beats writing it ourselves.
вЂўвЃ   вЃ Follow the standard agent-project layout as it grows: вЃ вЂЇagent/вЂЇвЃ  for core logic, вЃ вЂЇtools/вЂЇвЃ  for tool definitions, вЃ вЂЇtests/вЂЇвЃ  for tests. Flag any deviation.

## Idioms the user will meet often

When you use one of these for the first time in the codebase, add a one-line teaching note:
вЂўвЃ   вЃ вЃ вЂЇasyncвЂЇвЃ  / вЃ вЂЇawaitвЂЇвЃ  (Chapter 9)
вЂўвЃ   вЃ Decorators like вЃ вЂЇ@dataclassвЂЇвЃ , вЃ вЂЇ@app.get(...)вЂЇвЃ  (Chapter 5 / 11)
вЂўвЃ   вЃ Pydantic вЃ вЂЇBaseModelвЂЇвЃ  (Chapter 10)
вЂўвЃ   вЃ Context managers (вЃ вЂЇwith ... as ...вЂЇвЃ )
вЂўвЃ   вЃ List/dict comprehensions

After the first encounter, trust the user has seen it.